	$211310: 'Excellent job men.',
	$211320:
		'Sergeant Conti, get on the radio. Tell HQ our draw is clear for the tanks to come ashore.',
	$211322: "Okay. That's all the bunkers. Good work.",
	$211323: 'Now get to those 88s, you bastards.',
	$211324: 'Got a kraut bunker over here, just begging to get busted.',
	$211326: "There - that's another kraut bunker, right?",
	$211328: "Enemy bunker! Let's crack that thing open!",
	$211330: 'I need a casualty report. Redistribute weapons and ammo.',
	$211335: 'The Germans are reinforcing from those bunkers',
	$211338: "If we can blow 'em with satchel charges it'll take some pressure off our beachhead.",
	$211340:
		'Secure the perimeter and dig in. Inform Dog Company that we are in position and waiting for them to come ashore.',
	$211350:
		'SEVEN HUNDRED men died that morning on that tiny strip of sand. Another FIFTEEN HUNDRED, wounded. THREE HUNDRED missing, dragged under the waves.  Pearson.  Williams.  Krycinski... all good men.',
	$211360:
		'By sunset over ONE HUNDRED AND FIFTY SIX THOUSAND men had come ashore. The invasion had begun.',
	$211370: 'Or, as my C.O. used to say, ‘Hell opened its gates.’',
	$211380:
		'The night before, the largest airborne operation in history dropped 3 divisions of paratroopers behind enemy lines.',
	$211390:
		'And their objective was to seize major roadways and prevent a counterattack that could jeopardize the entire invasion.',
	$211400: 'Success on D-Day depended entirely on these men...',
	$211500: "Able company's scattered all across the beach.",
	$211510: 'We need to get to the shingle.',
	$211520: 'First squad is at the shingle.',
	$211522: 'We have squads at the shingle, but we need more!',
